  "text": "Z Q is the Q-quantile of the geopotential height for the particular latitude. For Q = 0.5, for example, only longitudes with geopotential heights in the mid-latitudes higher than the median are allowed for blocking. Thus, the anomaly of the geopotential height in the mid-latitudes has to be positive compared to the respective Q value for that latitude. This idea is motivated by a study of Dole and Gordon [CITATION_1] , who searched for persistent positive anomalies in the 500 hPa geopotential height field. With the criterion in (4) the number of cut-off lows is reduced (see Section 3). The Q-quantile is the threshold parameter to tune the stringency. However, this filter is not sufficient to demand synoptic scales of blocking highs.",
